  "prompt": "What will happen to the border between Northern Ireland and Ireland following the Brexit vote?",
  "response": "The future of the border between Northern Ireland and Ireland has been a significant concern following the Brexit vote. The UK\u2019s withdrawal from the EU raised challenges regarding how to manage this border, given that it is the only land border between the UK and the EU. \n\nAs part of the Brexit negotiations, the EU and the UK agreed on the Northern Ireland Protocol, which aims to avoid a hard border on the island of Ireland. Under the Protocol, Northern Ireland remains aligned with certain EU rules, particularly regarding goods, while still legally part of the UK's customs territory. This arrangement means that goods moving between Great Britain and Northern Ireland are subject to checks and controls to ensure compliance with EU standards, but goods moving between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland can continue to move without significant border checks.\n\nHowever, the implementation of the Northern Ireland Protocol has been contentious and politically sensitive. There have been efforts from both sides to relax some of the requirements or renegotiate the terms to ensure smoother trade flow and mitigate any economic impacts. The situation remains fluid, and ongoing discussions and negotiations may lead to adjustments in the implementation of the Protocol to address various concerns.\n\nIn summary, while the aim has been to avoid a hard border and protect the Good Friday Agreement, the practicalities of managing this border post-Brexit are still evolving and subject to political negotiations.",
